ROCm decode at 125 GB/s effective vs 220 GB/s target — 1.6x headroom

Status: OPEN (measured 2026-05-09).

Measurements (decode of canonical 30-token Strix Halo prompt, --temp 0)
- Wall: 71.0 ms/token = 14.10 t/s decode.
- DS4_TOP_PROFILE breakdown of metal_graph_eval_token_raw_swa_top:
    begin       : 0.000 ms
    encode (CPU): 7.0 ms (CPU enqueueing kernels)
    topk        : 0.001 ms
    end (sync)  : 65.0 ms  <-- GPU drain dominates
    read_top    : 0.000 ms (4-byte readback)
  total       : 72.0 ms
- Per-decode-token model reads: 8.9 GiB (gguf inventory):
    attention  4.88 GiB  (55%)
    routed MoE 1.70 GiB  (19%)
    shared FFN 1.07 GiB  (12%)
    HC         0.63 GiB  ( 7%)
    embed/out  0.52 GiB  ( 6%)
    other      < 0.10 GiB
- Effective decode bandwidth = 8.9 / 0.071 = 125 GB/s.
- Target (per user 2026-05-09): 220 GB/s effective + 100% GPU utilization.
- Ceiling at 220 GB/s = 23 t/s decode (43 ms/token). Headroom 1.6x.

Root cause
GPU is the bottleneck, not CPU sync. End_commands waits ~65 ms for GPU
to drain queued kernels. Per-kernel real GPU time (DS4_ROCM_SYNC_EACH=1
sync_each forces ROCM_TIME_SCOPE to measure actual GPU time):
  - matmul_q8_0_tensor          0.104 ms/call x 302/tok = 31 ms/token
  - matmul_f16_tensor           0.066 ms/call x 258/tok = 17 ms/token
  - routed_moe_one_tensor       0.299 ms/call x  42/tok = 12 ms/token
  - router_select_tensor        0.244 ms/call x  42/tok = 10 ms/token
  - matmul_q8_0_hc_expand       0.212 ms/call x  42/tok =  9 ms/token
  - attention_output_low_q8     0.181 ms/call x  42/tok =  8 ms/token
  - shared_gate_up_swiglu_q8    0.134 ms/call x  42/tok =  6 ms/token
  - matmul_f16_pair             0.109 ms/call x  60/tok =  7 ms/token
  - shared_down_hc_expand       0.066 ms/call x  42/tok =  3 ms/token
  - attention_decode_heads      0.073 ms/call x  42/tok =  3 ms/token
  Sum sync_each = ~106 ms/token; deferred-sync overlap recovers ~35 ms
  to reach the 71 ms wall. So overlap is ~33% gain already.

Levers to reach 220 GB/s
1. Per-kernel bandwidth audit (BIGGEST). Most kernels run at 70-85% of
   the 220 GB/s target. Audit each top-N kernel: measure achieved GB/s,
   identify cause of shortfall (unaligned loads, over-broadcast, etc.).
   - matmul_q8_0_tensor: 302 calls/token, biggest aggregate. Different
     call sites have different shapes (q_a, q_b, kv, attn_output_a/b,
     output, etc.). Need per-site timing.
   - routed_moe_one: per microbench at 188 GiB/s = 85% of 220 GB/s.
     ~17% headroom from in-block decode optimization or memory layout.
   - matmul_q8_0_hc_expand_tensor at 0.212 ms/call: HC expand is doing
     16384*24 fp16 matmul = 768 KB read. At 220 GB/s = 3.5 us.
     Observed 212 us = 60x slower. Massive per-call overhead.
2. Kernel fusion (SECOND-BIGGEST). Many small kernels with high per-call
   overhead are fusion candidates. router_select (244 us each, 42x/tok =
   10 ms/tok) could fuse into the matmul that produces router_logits.
   compressor_update (17 us each, 130x/tok = 2.2 ms) and rope_tail
   (10 us, 150x = 1.5 ms) are also high call-count.
3. CPU encode (smallest). 7 ms/token of CPU encoding. HIP graph capture
   (tsk-16) could cut this to <1 ms but only saves 6 ms = 8.5%.

Target breakdown (rough, to reach 23 t/s)
- Per-kernel optimization to 90% of 220 GB/s ceiling: -10 ms (1.16x)
- Top-3 kernel fusion: -8 ms (1.13x)
- HIP graph capture: -6 ms (1.09x)
- Combined: 71 -> ~47 ms = 21 t/s. Within striking distance of 23 t/s
  ceiling.

